ed Kingdom","of Cefnhafodau,Llangurig,Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1362–":"circa 1362–Overleden","1366–Female":"1366–Overleden","1388–Male":"1388–Overleden","1362–Male":"1362–Overleden","1379":"1379","1388":"1388","1366":"1366","1362":"1362","about 1388":"circa 1388","about 1362":"circa 1362","Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Cefnhafodau,Llangurig,Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1362–":"about 1362–Deceased","1366–Female":"1366–Deceased","1388–Male":"1388–Deceased","1362–Male":"1362–Deceased","1379":"1379","1388":"1388","1366":"1366","1362":"1362","about 1388":"about 1388","about 1362":"about 1362","Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Cefnhafodau,Llangurig,Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Philip ap Llywelyn was born about 1362, in Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom. He married verch Gwilym in 1379, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1362–":"umbes 1362–Surnud","1366–Female":"1366–Surnud","1388–Male":"1388–Surnud","1362–Male":"1362–Surnud","1379":"1379","1388":"1388","1366":"1366","1362":"1362","about 1388":"umbes 1388","about 1362":"umbes 1362","Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Cefnhafodau,Llangurig,Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1362–":"noin 1362–Kuollut","1366–Female":"1366–Kuollut","1388–Male":"1388–Kuollut","1362–Male":"1362–Kuollut","1379":"1379","1388":"1388","1366":"1366","1362":"1362","about 1388":"noin 1388","about 1362":"noin 1362","Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Cefnhafodau,Llangurig,Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1362–":"environ 1362–Décédé","1366–Female":"1366–Décédée","1388–Male":"1388–Décédé","1362–Male":"1362–Décédé","1379":"1379","1388":"1388","1366":"1366","1362":"1362","about 1388":"environ 1388","about 1362":"environ 1362","Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","of Cefnhafodau,Llangurig,Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Philip ap Llywelyn est né environ 1362, à Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé verch Gwilym en 1379, à Glamorgan, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"ab